{"id":"1708.03705","submitter":"Guiomar Ruiz Prof.","authors":"Guiomar Ruiz, Ugur Tirnakli, Ernesto P. Borges and Constantino Tsallis","title":"Statistical characterization of discrete conservative systems: The web\n  map","comments":"20 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 96, 042158 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.96.042158","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We numerically study the two-dimensional, area preserving, web map. When the\nmap is governed by ergodic behavior, it is, as expected, correctly described by\nBoltzmann-Gibbs statistics, based on the additive entropic functional\n$S_{BG}[p(x)] = -k\\int dx\\,p(x) \\ln p(x)$. In contrast, possible ergodicity\nbreakdown and transitory sticky dynamical behavior drag the map into the realm\nof generalized $q$-statistics, based on the nonadditive entropic functional\n$S_q[p(x)]=k\\frac{1-\\int dx\\,[p(x)]^q}{q-1}$ ($q \\in {\\cal R}; S_1=S_{BG}$). We\nstatistically describe the system (probability distribution of the sum of\nsuccessive iterates, sensitivity to the initial condition, and entropy\nproduction per unit time) for typical values of the parameter that controls the\nergodicity of the map. For small (large) values of the external parameter $K$,\nwe observe $q$-Gaussian distributions with $q=1.935\\dots$ (Gaussian\ndistributions), like for the standard map. In contrast, for intermediate values\nof $K$, we observe a different scenario, due to the fractal structure of the\ntrajectories embedded in the chaotic sea. Long-standing non-Gaussian\ndistributions are characterized in terms of the kurtosis and the box-counting\ndimension of chaotic sea.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 11 Aug 2017 21:10:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-11-08"}
